- No buffer size prediction (could read in chunks)
- Multiple function calls per character (getc + strbuf_grow)

3. Optimization Strategy:
The selected strategy of pre-allocating capacity applies well here since:
- We're dealing with a dynamically growing buffer
- Line lengths often follow patterns (we can make reasonable guesses)
- Memory reallocations are expensive for small increments

4. Proposed Optimization:
- Pre-allocate a reasonable initial buffer size (e.g., 128 bytes)
- Read characters in batches until terminator/EOF is found
- Only grow buffer when actually needed
- Maintain same functionality but with fewer allocations

5. Selected Optimization:
Implement chunked reading with initial buffer reservation to minimize reallocations.

